and it is a matter equally familiar that houses, churehes, even castles, were wholly or in part built of tim- ber. “ The use of wood for domestic architecture long after this time,'’— the eleventh century—says Profes- sor Freeman (Norm. Stone was at this time fast coming into use for do- mestic, as well as for military and ecclesiasticae buildings.” Previously then the material in use must have been wood, or modifications depend- ing on the use of wood. As an illustration simply, let me advert to Greensted church, constructed, as there seems no reason to doubt, in or about the year 1013, to receive the body of St. Edmund.
